Olist¶

Introduction¶

This is a Brazilian ecommerce public dataset of orders made at Olist Store. The dataset has information of 100k orders from 2016 to 2018 made at multiple marketplaces in Brazil. Its features allows viewing an order from multiple dimensions: from order status, price, payment and freight performance to customer location, product attributes and finally reviews written by customers. We also released a geolocation dataset that relates Brazilian zip codes to lat/lng coordinates.

This is real commercial data, it has been anonymised, and references to the companies and partners in the review text have been replaced with the names of Game of Thrones great houses.

Business Model¶

This dataset was generously provided by Olist, the largest department store in Brazilian marketplaces. Olist connects small businesses from all over Brazil to channels without hassle and with a single contract. Those merchants are able to sell their products through the Olist Store and ship them directly to the customers using Olist logistics partners.

After a customer purchases the product from Olist Store a seller gets notified to fulfill that order. Once the customer receives the product, or the estimated delivery date is due, the customer gets a satisfaction survey by email where he can give a note for the purchase experience and write down some comments.

An order might have multiple items. Each item might be fulfilled by a distinct seller. All text identifying stores and partners where replaced by the names of Game of Thrones great houses.

Focus is to explore the dataset and derive recommended actions for Olist.

Investigate what's driving low reviews¶

As Olist is facing consumers as the onlineshop and not the small sellers, any hit in reputation is negatively affecting Olist's business. This means any bad reviews from customers will lead to Olist's customer rating at Amazon and other marketplaces will go down, decreasing the likelyhood of customers buying at olist.

Let's investigate what is driving the low ratings.

In [57]:
plt.xlim([0.5,5.5])
plt.title('Number of orders by rating')
plt.hist(x=order_data.review_score, bins=np.arange(7)-0.5);
In [58]:
np.sum(order_data.review_score <= 3)/len(order_data)
Out[58]:
0.2107562815895717

Over 21% of reviews have a score of 3 and below, which is major cost for Olist. Reducing the drivers for negative reviews will positive impact overall business performance

Sellers/Products as driver for negative reviews¶

Products and sellers will likely have a larger impact on the reviews as customers will judge the quality of the products for the majority of the reviews.

We will assume there's cost linked to negative reviews - as Olist is the merchant which faces consumers on Amazon or other marketplaces, negative reviews decrease the overall reputation of Olist on that platform and will lead to customers not purchasing from Olist.

We will assume that there's no additional cost for Olist.

Calculating Costs from bad reviews¶

cost_reviews_dict = {1: 100, 2: 50, 3: 40, 4: 0, 5:0}

Calculating costs and profit per seller¶

Olist's revenue source is taking a 10% cut from sellers' sales + 80 BRL fee per month for being listed on Olist.

With this information we can calculate the revenue generated by each seller, cost from reviews profit per seller.

In [76]:
seller_df = Seller().get_training_data().copy()

#Merging seller information with cost from reviews dataframe. Relevant is 
seller_df = seller_df.merge(cost_reviews_df, on="seller_id", how="outer")
seller_df["revenues"] = seller_df["sales"]*0.1+80*seller_df["months_on_olist"]
seller_df.revenues = seller_df.revenues.fillna(0)
seller_df["profit"] = seller_df.revenues - seller_df.review_cost

Removing sellers with negative profit will lead to improved profitability for Olist

Let's calculate improved profitability for Olist when removing retailers with negative profit for Olist¶
